---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Hydration Breaks and Heat Waves: The Hidden Tactical Variable" description="With extreme summer temperatures in host cities, we analyze how it changes tactics.">
  <main class="min-h-screen py-20 px-4 bg-[#f9a8d4]">
    <article class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl bg-white border-[4px] border-black p-8 md:p-12 shadow-[12px_12px_0px_#000] relative z-20">
      <div class="inline-block bg-yellow-300 text-black border-[3px] border-black font-black px-4 py-1 uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">TACTICS & CLIMATE</div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-black text-black uppercase tracking-tighter mb-6 leading-none" style="font-family: 'Anton', sans-serif;">
        Hydration Breaks and Heat Waves: The Hidden Tactical Variable
      </h1>
      
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black font-medium leading-relaxed">
        <p class="text-xl font-bold mb-8 p-4 bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-black border-l-8 border-l-pink-500">
          Everyone is talking about formations and wonderkids, but nobody is talking about the weather. Playing high-press football in Houston in mid-July is going to literally cook some of these teams.
        </p>
        
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mt-12 mb-4" style="font-family: 'Anton', sans-serif;">1. The Death of the High Press?</h2>
        <p>
          You cannot run a Jurgen Klopp style *Gegenpress* for 90 minutes when it is 95 degrees Fahrenheit with 80% humidity in Miami or Monterrey. Teams that rely on out-working their opponents are going to gas out by the 60th minute. The meta is going to shift to possession-based, low-block styles simply for survival.
        </p>
        
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mt-12 mb-4" style="font-family: 'Anton', sans-serif;">2. Tactical Timeouts (Hydration Breaks)</h2>
        <p>
          Mandatory hydration breaks at the 30-minute and 75-minute marks act like basketball timeouts. Managers are going to use these pauses to completely flip their tactical shapes. If a team is getting battered, expect the manager to use the water break to kill momentum and restructure the defense. It's no longer just a physical break; it's a massive tactical weapon.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-black uppercase mt-12 mb-4" style="font-family: 'Anton', sans-serif;">3. The Squad Depth Advantage</h2>
        <p>
          With 5 substitutions allowed per match, squad depth is going to be the ultimate decider. The nations that can bring 5 fresh, elite players off the bench at the 60-minute mark to run against an exhausted, heat-stroked defense will win the tournament. Having a stacked starting XI isn't enough anymore; you need a stacked bench.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-12 flex justify-between items-center border-t-[4px] border-black pt-6">
        <a href="/blog" class="font-anton text-xl uppercase text-black hover:text-pink-500 transition-colors">← Back to Guides</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
